In February 2014, CHIKV had already reached continental territory, when autochthonous infections were observed in French Guiana, the first country in South America to declare CHIKV infection. At this point, the dispersion of CHIKV to other American countries was only a matter of time. From 2014 to 2015, more than 16,000 individuals were infected in French Guiana. Importantly, infections presented several atypical cases, such as neurological disorders, cardio-respiratory failure, acute hepatitis, acute pancreatitis, renal disorders, and muscular impairment. Only two deaths associated with CHIKF during this period were documented (
 Bonifay et al., 2018; 
 Figure 1B).
